
[1]relax

   RELAX', v.t. [L. relaxo; re and laxo, to slacken.]

   1. To slacken; to make less tense or rigid; as, to relax a rope or
   cord; to relax the muscles or sinews; to relax the reins in riding.

   2. To loosen; to make less close or firm; as, to relax the joints.

   3. To make less severe or rigorous; to remit or abate in strictness;
   as, to relax a law or rule of justice; to relax a demand.

   4. To remit or abate in attention, assiduity or labor; as, to relax
   study; to relax exertions or efforts.

   5. To unbend; to ease; to relieve from close attention; as,
   conversation relaxes the student or the mind.

   6. To relieve from constipation; to loosen; to open; as, medicines
   relax the bowels.

   7. To open; to loose.

   8. To make languid.

                                RELAX', v.i.

   1. To abate in severity; to become more mild or less rigorous.

   In others she relax'd again, and govern'd with a looser rein.

   2. To remit in close attention. It is useful for the student to relax
   often, and give himself to exercise and amusements.

                     RELAX', n. Relaxation. [Not used.]
